<org.eclipse.epf.uma:TaskDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:rmc="http://www.ibm.com/rmc" rmc:version="7.5.1" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmi:id="-Gk0us3kdvPV_WhImiBC_Yw" name="Verify system adn HW SW design,_tXIJkJzdEeCBU9GxbrSLZw" guid="-Gk0us3kdvPV_WhImiBC_Yw" changeDate="2011-08-24T04:48:40.100-0700" version="7.5.1">
  <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    In this task the system design can be verified through the following methods:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;blockquote style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;p>&#xD;
        System design inspection, which is recommended for items with an ASIL of A and highly recommended for items with an&#xD;
        ASIL of B,C or D&#xD;
    &lt;/p>&#xD;
    &lt;p>&#xD;
        System design walk-through, which is recommended for items with an ASIL of B and highly recommended for items with&#xD;
        an ASIL of A, this technique is not recommended for ASILs C or D&#xD;
    &lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;/blockquote>&#xD;
&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;>&#xD;
    These techniques are used&amp;nbsp;to check that the technical safety requirements have been detailed and implemented&#xD;
    correctly in the design.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;blockquote style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;p>&#xD;
        Simulation, System prototyping and vehicle tests are all recommended for items with an ASIL of A or B and highly&#xD;
        recommended for items with an ASIL of C or D.&#xD;
    &lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;/blockquote>&#xD;
&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;>&#xD;
    If system based modeling is used, simulation is possible based upon using&amp;nbsp; the verification task from &lt;a&#xD;
    class=&quot;elementLink&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../process.syseng.base-ibm/deliveryprocesses/Architectural%20Design%20-%20uc_E8CAF5DD.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_H1zdAa3hEd63sNXoX4A_sA&quot;>Architectural Design - Use-Case based&lt;/a>. These techniques can also be used as a method&#xD;
    for fault injection&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;>&#xD;
    Safety Analysis as detailed in &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../practice.compliance.iso26262.base-ibm/tasks/Develop%20technical%20safety%20concept_E39D80C1.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_1NTrcJwIEeCHd41ThlqoSg&quot;>Develop technical safety concept&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;step 2 and in ISO 26262, volume 9, clause 8.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    If the result of this verification procedure is that&amp;nbsp;new hazards are identified that are not part of the&#xD;
    safety&amp;nbsp;goal then the user is referred to ISO 26262, volume 4 clause 7.4.8.2 for guidance.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;br dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;justify&quot; />&#xD;
    &lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
  <purpose>To show that the technical safety concepts that have been developed are workable for the system design proposed.</purpose>
</org.eclipse.epf.uma:TaskDescription>
